const a = [
  {"id":1722,"text":"Which of the following drugs is a 5-lipoxygenase pathway inhibitor?","explanation":"The drug **zileuton** is a 5-lipoxygenase pathway inhibitor. The 5-lipoxygenase pathway plays a crucial role in the production of leukotrienes, which are inflammatory mediators involved in various allergic and inflammatory conditions, including asthma.\r\nBy blocking this pathway, it helps to alleviate inflammation and bronchoconstriction in conditions such as asthma.\r\n\r\nUnlike other asthma medications that primarily target bronchodilation or inflammation, Zileuton specifically targets the 5-lipoxygenase pathway, providing an alternative approach to managing asthma symptoms. It is usually prescribed as an adjunct therapy in patients who require additional control of their asthma symptoms despite using other asthma medications.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 712.","responses":[{"text":"Zileuton","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Theophylline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cromolyn","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monteluklast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omalizumab","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1782,"text":"What disease is characterized by Charcot Leyden crystals and Curschmann's spirals found in sputum?","explanation":"**Bronchial asthma** is a chronic inflammatory disorder of the airways characterized by recurrent episodes of wheezing, breathlessness, chest tightness, and cough. The condition is associated with increased airway reactivity and inflammation, leading to bronchospasm and airflow limitation.\r\n\r\nCharcot-Leyden crystals and Curschmann's spirals are characteristic findings in the sputum of individuals with bronchial asthma. Charcot-Leyden crystals are hexagonal-shaped crystals derived from the breakdown of eosinophils, which are a type of white blood cell involved in the allergic response. Curschmann's spirals are spiral-shaped mucus plugs formed from the accumulation of tenacious mucus in the airways.\r\n\r\nThe presence of these two findings in the sputum is indicative of the underlying inflammatory process in bronchial asthma. They can be identified during microscopic examination of the sputum and can help in the diagnosis and management of the condition.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 699, 724.","responses":[{"text":"Bronchiectasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchial asthma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1790,"text":"A 35-year-old female brings her pleural fluid analysis report, which shows the exudative nature of pleural fluid with a high amylase level. She gives a history of upper abdominal pain and vomiting in the recent past. She also had pulmonary tuberculosis 10 years ago. She has now developed pleural effusion. What is the most likely cause of her current condition?","explanation":"The most likely cause of the patient's current condition, characterized by an exudative pleural effusion with a high amylase level, is **acute pancreatitis**. Acute pancreatitis is an inflammatory condition of the pancreas that can lead to the release of pancreatic enzymes into the bloodstream and surrounding tissues. In some cases, these enzymes can reach the pleural space, resulting in the presence of amylase in the pleural fluid.\r\n\r\nThe patient's history of upper abdominal pain and vomiting is suggestive of acute pancreatitis, as these are common symptoms associated with the condition. The previous history of pulmonary tuberculosis is unrelated to the current presentation.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that other causes of exudative pleural effusion should also be considered and evaluated, such as malignancy or infections. However, given the high amylase level in the pleural fluid and the patient's clinical presentation, acute pancreatitis is the most likely cause in this scenario.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 563.","responses":[{"text":"Malignancy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1825,"text":"A medicolegal doctor is called to perform a post-mortem examination. He gives an incision starting from one inch below the symphysis menti up to symphysis pubis without cutting the umbilicus. What is this incision called?","explanation":"The incision described, starting from one inch below the symphysis menti (chin) up to the symphysis pubis without cutting the umbilicus, is called an **I-shaped incision**. This incision is commonly used in forensic medicine and post-mortem examinations.\r\n\r\nThe I-shaped incision allows for easy access to the thoracic and abdominal cavities for examination of organs and structures. The incision begins at the chin and extends vertically down to the pubic region, following the midline of the body. By avoiding the umbilicus, it allows for a clear view and access to the organs without interfering with the abdominal structures.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 102.","responses":[{"text":"Y-shaped incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cruciate incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"I-shaped incision","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified Y-shaped- incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-shaped incision","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1828,"text":"A 24-year-old asthmatic lady becomes pregnant. On examination, she has severe bilateral bronchospasm. Which of the following complications might she develop due to uncontrolled asthma?","explanation":"Uncontrolled asthma in a pregnant woman can lead to various complications for both the mother and the fetus. One of the potential complications is **maternal eclampsia**.\r\n\r\nMaternal eclampsia, also known as preeclampsia with seizures, is a serious condition characterized by high blood pressure and seizures during pregnancy. Although the exact cause of eclampsia is not fully understood, it is believed to be related to abnormal placental development and poor blood supply to the placenta.\r\n\r\nIn the case of uncontrolled asthma, the persistent bronchospasm and inadequate oxygen supply to the mother can lead to decreased oxygen delivery to the placenta. This compromised oxygen supply can contribute to placental dysfunction and increase the risk of developing preeclampsia and eclampsia.\r\n\r\nMaternal eclampsia poses significant risks to both the mother and the fetus. It can result in maternal complications such as stroke, organ damage, and even maternal death. Additionally, it can cause fetal growth restriction, premature birth, and fetal distress.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 570.","responses":[{"text":"Intrauterine growth retardation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maternal eclampsia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fetal cardiac defects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spina bifida","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post date delivery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1831,"text":"A 35-year-old female presents to the outpatient department with progressive shortness of breath and dry cough. She has a history of red eyes as well. Chest X-Ray shows bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, widespread pulmonary lines, and honeycombing. Which of the following is the best diagnostic test?","explanation":"In a patient presenting with progressive shortness of breath, dry cough, red eyes, and radiographic findings of bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, widespread pulmonary lines, and honeycombing, the most appropriate diagnostic test is a **lung biopsy**.\r\n\r\nThese clinical findings are suggestive of a granulomatous lung disease, and the differential diagnosis includes conditions such as sarcoidosis, hypersensitivity pneumonitis, and certain types of interstitial lung diseases.\r\n\r\nA lung biopsy allows for a definitive diagnosis by examining lung tissue histologically. It helps identify the presence of granulomas, their distribution, and other characteristic features that can differentiate between different causes of granulomatous lung disease.\r\n\r\nOther diagnostic tests such as serum ACE (angiotensin-converting enzyme) levels, bronchoalveolar lavage, high-resolution CT (HRCT), and pulmonary function tests can provide additional supportive information, but they may not provide a definitive diagnosis. The lung biopsy provides direct visualization and examination of lung tissue, which is essential for accurate diagnosis and appropriate management.","reference":"1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 693.\r\n\r\n\r\n2) Bokhari SRA, Zulfiqar H, Mansur A. Sarcoidosis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 17, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430687/\r\n\r\n3) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 607, 609-610.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary function test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchoalveolar lavage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung biopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum ACE level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest high-resolution CT (HRCT)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1836,"text":"A 2-year-old girl is brought to the emergency room with complaints of high-grade fever, noisy breathing, and drooling for 1 day. On examination, temperature = 104°F and respiratory rate = 60/min. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"In a 2-year-old girl presenting with high-grade fever, noisy breathing, drooling, and respiratory distress, the most likely diagnosis is **epiglottitis**. \r\n\r\nEpiglottitis is a severe bacterial infection involving the epiglottis and surrounding structures, usually caused by Haemophilus influenzae type B (Hib) bacteria. It typically presents with sudden onset of symptoms, including high fever, sore throat, difficulty swallowing, and respiratory distress. The child may prefer to sit upright and may exhibit a characteristic \"sniffing dog\" position to maintain airway patency.\r\n\r\nThe presence of drooling, noisy breathing, and respiratory distress is concerning for upper airway obstruction, a characteristic feature of epiglottitis. The high fever further supports this diagnosis.\r\n\r\nPrompt recognition and management are crucial in epiglottitis to prevent life-threatening airway compromise. The child should be stabilized with appropriate airway support, and intravenous antibiotics effective against Hib should be initiated.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 85.","responses":[{"text":"Peritonsillar abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute laryngeotracheobronchtis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spasmodic croup","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epiglottitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial tracheitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1839,"text":"A 4-year-old boy has a 1-month history of recurrent cough with wheezing. There is no history of previous similar complaints and no family history of asthma or tuberculosis. Examination shows enlarged cervical nodes and bronchi. Chest X-Ray shows air trapping on the right side during inspiration. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"In a 4-year-old boy with a 1-month history of recurrent cough with wheezing, enlarged cervical nodes, and findings of air trapping on chest X-ray, the most likely diagnosis is **foreign body aspiration**.\r\n\r\nForeign body aspiration occurs when a foreign object enters the airway and obstructs the bronchi, leading to respiratory symptoms such as cough, wheezing, and difficulty breathing. It commonly occurs in young children who tend to explore objects by putting them in their mouths.\r\n\r\nThe presence of wheezing and air trapping on the right side during inspiration suggests partial obstruction of the right main bronchus, causing air to be trapped in the affected lung segment.\r\n\r\nEnlarged cervical nodes may indicate reactive lymphadenopathy due to the presence of an inflammatory process in the airways.\r\n\r\nA thorough history, clinical examination, and imaging findings support the diagnosis of foreign body aspiration in this case. Prompt evaluation and appropriate intervention, such as bronchoscopy, are necessary to remove the foreign object and relieve the obstruction.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: \r\n669, 671, 683.","responses":[{"text":"Gastro esophageal reflux","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reactive airway disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nodal tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foreign body aspiration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right middle lobe syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1842,"text":"A 6-year-old male child is brought to the emergency room because of recurrent wheezing. He is on inhaled steroids. His mother gives a history that he has daytime symptoms\u003e 2/week and nighttime symptoms \u003e 2/months. On spirometry, his FEV is \u003e 80% with a PEF variability of 30%. He gets diagnosed with asthma. What is the classification of severity of asthma in this patient?","explanation":"The classification of asthma severity is based on the frequency and severity of symptoms, as well as lung function measurements. In this case, the child has daytime symptoms more than two times per week and nighttime symptoms more than two times per month, which places him in the category of persistent asthma.\r\n\r\nThe spirometry results show that his forced expiratory volume (FEV) is greater than 80%, indicating mild airflow limitation. The peak expiratory flow (PEF) variability of 30% suggests some variability in lung function.\r\n\r\nAccording to the Global Initiative for Asthma (GINA) guidelines, **mild persistent asthma** is characterized by symptoms occurring more than twice a week, but not daily, and nighttime symptoms more than twice a month. Lung function measurements, such as FEV, are usually greater than 80%, and PEF variability is greater than 20% but less than 30%.","reference":"1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 530.\r\n\r\n2) Dusser D, Montani D, Chanez P, et al. Mild asthma: an expert review on epidemiology, clinical characteristics and treatment recommendations. Allergy.","responses":[{"text":"Mild intermittent asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cough variant asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mild persistent asthma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Moderate persistent asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe persistent asthma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1845,"text":"A middle-aged male presents with a two-week history of severe shortness of breath and fever. On examination, he is cyanosed with bilateral coarse crepitations all over the chest. Chest X-Ray shows bilateral lung infiltrates, with O2 saturation of 88% on room air. What is the next best investigation as part of management?","explanation":"The next best investigation as part of the management in this case would be a **high-resolution CT (HRCT) scan**.\r\n\r\nThe clinical presentation of severe shortness of breath, fever, bilateral lung infiltrates, and low oxygen saturation raises suspicion of a significant lung pathology such as diffuse parenchymal lung disease. HRCT is a valuable imaging modality that provides detailed and high-resolution images of the lung parenchyma, allowing for the evaluation of lung architecture and identification of specific abnormalities. It can help differentiate between different lung conditions, such as pneumonia, interstitial lung disease, or pulmonary edema, which may present with similar clinical features.\r\n\r\nHRCT is particularly useful in this case because it can provide additional information about the extent and distribution of the lung infiltrates, the presence of any underlying lung pathology, and help guide further management decisions. It can also assist in the diagnosis of specific conditions, such as identifying characteristic patterns in interstitial lung diseases.","reference":"1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 605.\r\n\r\n2) Masood I, Elyassi W, Rind W. Medicine. 3rd ed. Majeed Sons; 2018: 241.","responses":[{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ESR and CRP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterial blood gases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High resolution CT","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1850,"text":"A 28-year-old female came with acute shortness of breath for one day. She is experiencing night symptoms for the past 2 months. What is the cause of raised diffusion capacity for carbon monoxide (DLCO) in pulmonary function tests?","explanation":"DLCO measures the ability of the lungs to transfer carbon monoxide from inhaled air to the bloodstream. In **asthma**, the raised DLCO is attributed to increased ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) mismatch due to bronchoconstriction and airway inflammation. The airway inflammation causes a decrease in airway diameter and increased resistance, leading to airflow limitation and impaired ventilation. However, the alveolar-capillary membrane remains intact, allowing efficient gas exchange and resulting in an increased DLCO.\r\n\r\nIn conditions such as obstructive sleep apnea, emphysema, cardiac failure, and interstitial lung disease, the DLCO is usually reduced due to impaired gas exchange at the alveolar-capillary membrane. These conditions are associated with decreased lung compliance, structural lung abnormalities, and impaired diffusion capacity.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 699.","responses":[{"text":"Asthma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive sleep apnea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial lung disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1853,"text":"A 70-year-old male patient, a heavy smoker, previously diagnosed case of COPD, has presented with cough, hemoptysis, low-grade fever, significant weight loss, and anorexia. X-ray chest reveals a large, left-sided pleural effusion. Pleural fluid analysis is done which is suggestive of exudative pleural effusion, according to Light's criteria. According to Light's criteria, exudate is likely if which of the following criteria has been met?","explanation":"According to Light's criteria, exudative pleural effusion is likely if the **pleural fluid protein: serum protein ratio is greater than 0.5**. \r\n\r\nLight's criteria are used to differentiate between exudative and transudative pleural effusions. Exudative effusions are usually associated with underlying inflammatory or malignant conditions, while transudative effusions are typically caused by systemic factors such as heart failure or liver disease.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the patient's presentation of cough, hemoptysis, low-grade fever, weight loss, and anorexia along with the presence of a large, left-sided pleural effusion suggests an inflammatory or malignant etiology. The pleural fluid analysis revealing an exudative nature based on Light's criteria supports this possibility.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 564.","responses":[{"text":"Pleural fluid LDH: serum LDH ratio\u003c0.6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural fluid protein: serum protein ratio \u003c0.5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural fluid protein: serum protein ratio \u003e0.5","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural fluid LDH \u003c two thirds of the upper limit of normal serum LDH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural fluid LDH: serum LDH ratio\u003c0.3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1856,"text":"Caplan syndrome consists of which of the following?","explanation":"Caplan syndrome is a specific clinical entity characterized by the presence of **rheumatoid arthritis (RA) in combination with pneumoconiosis**, particularly coal worker's pneumoconiosis or silicosis. It is important to note that Caplan syndrome is specifically associated with pneumoconiosis and not other forms of interstitial lung disease.\r\n\r\nThe syndrome was first described in coal miners with concomitant RA, but it can also occur in individuals exposed to other dust particles, such as silica. The pathogenesis of Caplan syndrome is not completely understood, but it is believed to involve the interaction between environmental exposures and an underlying genetic predisposition to developing RA.\r\n\r\nClinically, Caplan syndrome presents with characteristic nodular pulmonary opacities on chest radiographs, which are termed \"rheumatoid nodules.\" These nodules are typically found in the upper lobes of the lungs.","reference":"Nemakayala DR, Surmachevska N, Ramphul K. Caplan syndrome. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 16, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499886/","responses":[{"text":"Pneumoconiosis  and rheumatoid arthritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestosis and tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silicosis and tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Berriliosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Byssinosis and rheumatoid arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1858,"text":"Clinically, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) include which of the following?","explanation":"Clinically, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) encompasses two main subtypes: **chronic bronchitis and emphysema**. These two conditions share certain common features but also have distinct characteristics.\r\n\r\nChronic bronchitis is characterized by a chronic cough with sputum production for at least three months in two consecutive years. It is primarily a disease of the large airways, involving inflammation and narrowing of the bronchi. The chronic inflammation leads to increased mucus production and thickening of the bronchial walls, contributing to airflow limitation.\r\n\r\nEmphysema, on the other hand, is characterized by the destruction of the alveolar walls and loss of lung elasticity. This results in enlarged air spaces and decreased gas exchange surface area. Emphysema primarily affects the smaller airways and alveoli.\r\n\r\nIn clinical practice, many patients with COPD may exhibit features of both chronic bronchitis and emphysema to varying degrees, leading to overlapping symptoms and lung function abnormalities.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 674.","responses":[{"text":"Asthma and bronchiectasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic bronchitis and emphysema","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema and bronchiolitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiectasis and emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema and asthma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1890,"text":"In case of suicidal death, an investigation conducted by friends and relatives of the deceased for collecting information and knowledge about mental status in order to justify the suicide is called:","explanation":"In cases of suicidal death, a **psychological autopsy** is conducted to gather information and gain insight into the mental state of the deceased individual leading up to the suicide. It is a methodical investigation performed by friends, family members, mental health professionals, and law enforcement personnel.\r\n\r\nThe purpose of a psychological autopsy is to collect information about the individual's life history, behavior, relationships, and any significant events or stressors preceding the suicide. This includes interviews with family members, friends, and healthcare providers, as well as a review of available medical and psychiatric records.\r\n\r\nThe aim of a psychological autopsy is to gain a comprehensive understanding of the individual's psychological well-being, including any signs of mental illness, suicidal ideation, or previous suicide attempts. The collected information can help in determining the factors that may have contributed to the suicide and provide insights for prevention and intervention strategies.","reference":"Respiratory module, Forensic-medicine lecture slides, Topic: Autopsy-I, Subtopic: Psychological autopsy.","responses":[{"text":"Police autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medical autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Death investigation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Forensic autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Psychological autopsy","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1897,"text":"Which of the following is a key component of photochemical smog?","explanation":"Photochemical smog is a type of air pollution that forms when sunlight reacts with certain pollutants in the atmosphere, primarily nitrogen oxides (NOx) and volatile organic compounds (VOCs). Ozone (O3) is formed as a result of these reactions.\r\n\r\nIn the presence of sunlight, nitrogen oxides and volatile organic compounds undergo a series of chemical reactions that produce a variety of pollutants, including ozone. **Ozone at ground level** is a harmful pollutant that can cause respiratory problems, eye irritation, and other health issues. It is different from the beneficial ozone layer in the upper atmosphere, which protects the Earth from harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation.\r\n\r\nThe formation of ozone in photochemical smog is a complex process involving the interaction of sunlight, nitrogen oxides, and volatile organic compounds. These reactions occur primarily in urban and industrial areas where there are high levels of pollution from vehicles, industrial emissions, and other sources.","reference":"Lu H, Lyu X, Cheng H, Ling Z, Guo H. Overview on the spatial-temporal characteristics of the ozone formation regime in China. Environmental Science. Processes \u0026 Impacts.","responses":[{"text":"Ozone layer in upper atmosphere","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrocarbons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biological pollutants","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Particulate matter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ozone at ground level","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1908,"text":"Which of the following drugs blocks the 5-lipoxygenase enzyme and inhibits the synthesis of leukotriene?","explanation":"**Zileuton** is a drug that blocks the 5-lipoxygenase enzyme, thereby inhibiting the synthesis of leukotrienes. Leukotrienes are inflammatory mediators that play a significant role in the pathogenesis of asthma and other inflammatory conditions.\r\n\r\nBy inhibiting the action of 5-lipoxygenase, zileuton reduces the production of leukotrienes, specifically leukotriene B4, leukotriene C4, and leukotriene D4. These leukotrienes are known to cause bronchoconstriction, inflammation, and mucus production in the airways, leading to the symptoms of asthma.\r\n\r\nZileuton is used as a controller medication in the management of asthma. It helps to prevent and control asthma symptoms by reducing airway inflammation and improving lung function. It is particularly beneficial in patients with persistent asthma who have an inadequate response to other asthma medications.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that zileuton may have some side effects, including liver function abnormalities, so regular monitoring of liver function is necessary during treatment.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 712.","responses":[{"text":"Azelastine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zafirlukast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Montelukast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omalizumab","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zileuton","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1915,"text":"What is the amount of air a person can breathe in beginning at the normal expiratory level and distending the lungs to the maximum amount?","explanation":"The **inspiratory capacity** is a measurement of lung volume that represents the maximum volume of air a person can inspire after a normal expiration.\r\n\r\nThe inspiratory capacity is calculated by adding the tidal volume (the volume of air inspired and expired during normal breathing) to the inspiratory reserve volume (the additional volume of air that can be inhaled after a normal inspiration).\r\n\r\nThe inspiratory capacity provides valuable information about lung function and respiratory health. It is often measured during pulmonary function tests to assess lung volumes and capacities, diagnose respiratory conditions, and monitor disease progression or response to treatment.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 688.","responses":[{"text":"Inspiratory capacity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Functional residual capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vital capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Expiratory capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total lung capacity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1916,"text":"The DNA damage due to radicals formed as a result of radiation is an example of which of the following?","explanation":"The DNA damage caused by radicals formed as a result of radiation is an example of **indirect damage**. Indirect damage refers to the damage caused by the reactive intermediates generated by the interaction of radiation with molecules in the body, rather than direct interaction between the radiation and DNA.\r\n\r\nWhen ionizing radiation interacts with water molecules in the body, it produces free radicals, such as hydroxyl radicals (·OH), which are highly reactive and can cause oxidative damage to DNA. These free radicals can directly attack the DNA molecule, leading to DNA strand breaks, base modifications, and other types of DNA damage.\r\n\r\nThe DNA damage caused by these radicals can have various biological consequences, including cell death, mutations, and potentially the development of cancer.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 429.","responses":[{"text":"Direct damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splitting of chemical bonds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accidental damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect damage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Threshold level damage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1920,"text":"Which of the following is the most important cause of panacinar (panlobular) emphysema?","explanation":"The most important cause of panacinar (panlobular) emphysema, a type of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), is **alpha 1 antitrypsin deficiency**. Alpha 1 antitrypsin is a protein produced by the liver that helps protect the lungs from the damaging effects of enzymes called proteases. In individuals with alpha 1 antitrypsin deficiency, there is a decreased production or abnormal function of this protein, leading to an imbalance between proteases and their inhibitors in the lung tissue.\r\n\r\nPanacinar emphysema is characterized by the destruction of alveolar walls throughout the entire respiratory acinus, from the respiratory bronchioles to the alveoli. This leads to the enlargement of air spaces and loss of elastic recoil, resulting in air trapping and impaired airflow. While cigarette smoking is the most common cause of emphysema overall, alpha 1 antitrypsin deficiency is specifically associated with the development of panacinar emphysema, especially in younger individuals with a family history of the condition.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 675.","responses":[{"text":"Air pollution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cigarette smoking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occupational dust","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha 1 antitrypsin deficiency","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1921,"text":"The type of asphyxia that is associated with anesthesia and surgical maneuvers is termed as:","explanation":"The type of asphyxia that is associated with anesthesia and surgical maneuvers is termed **iatrogenic asphyxia**. \"Iatrogenic\" refers to conditions or complications that are caused by medical intervention or treatment.\r\n\r\nDuring anesthesia and surgical procedures, there can be various factors that contribute to iatrogenic asphyxia. These may include airway obstruction, inadequate ventilation, or compromised oxygenation due to the effects of anesthesia or surgical manipulation.\r\n\r\nExamples of situations that can lead to iatrogenic asphyxia include the accidental placement of an endotracheal tube in the esophagus instead of the trachea, inadequate oxygen supply during surgery, or complications such as laryngospasm or bronchospasm.\r\n\r\nPrompt recognition and intervention are crucial in managing iatrogenic asphyxia to prevent severe respiratory compromise and potential adverse outcomes.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 161.","responses":[{"text":"Pathological asphyxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clinical asphyxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mechanical asphyxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Toxic asphyxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iatrogenic asphyxia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1923,"text":"A medico-legal doctor is performing the autopsy for the opening of the skull during post-mortem in a newborn baby. How should the incision be done?","explanation":"During the autopsy of a newborn baby, the incision for opening the skull is typically done by opening the **sagittal and coronal sutures**. The sagittal suture is the main suture that runs along the midline of the skull from the anterior fontanelle (soft spot) to the posterior fontanelle. The coronal suture runs horizontally from one side of the skull to the other.\r\n\r\nTo open the skull, the medico-legal doctor makes a cut along the sagittal suture and then continues the incision along the coronal suture. This allows for a flap-like opening of the skull, providing access to the brain and its structures.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 321.","responses":[{"text":"Cutting along sagittal sutures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Over the top of the head from right ear to the left ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Making a circular cut","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cutting from mastoid to mastoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening of sagittal + coronal sutures","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1924,"text":"The most important difference between a forensic autopsy and a pathological autopsy is that in forensic autopsy:","explanation":"The most important difference between a forensic autopsy and a pathological autopsy is that a forensic autopsy is a **valid documentary evidence in the court of law**. Forensic autopsies are performed in cases of unnatural, sudden, or suspicious deaths with the primary purpose of gathering evidence and determining the cause and manner of death. The findings and documentation from a forensic autopsy can be presented as evidence in legal proceedings.\r\n\r\nWhile both forensic and pathological autopsies involve the examination of the deceased, the focus and objectives differ. Pathological autopsies are primarily performed to study the underlying disease processes and understand the cause of death for medical and research purposes. In contrast, forensic autopsies are conducted within a legal framework to investigate potential crimes, determine the cause of death, identify any injuries or signs of foul play, and provide expert testimony in legal proceedings.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 98.","responses":[{"text":"Cause of death is usually not known but has to be determined","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All cavities are opened even if injury is not found","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External findings are of vital importance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Done in cases of unnatural sudden or suspicious deaths","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a valid documentary evidence in the court of law","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1925,"text":"What is the main advantage of R. Virchow's technique of autopsy?","explanation":"The main advantage of Rudolf Virchow's technique of autopsy is that **each organ can be studied in detail**. Virchow's technique, also known as the \"systematic autopsy,\" emphasizes a thorough examination of each organ system to identify and document any abnormalities or pathological changes. This meticulous approach allows for a comprehensive understanding of the disease processes and contributes to accurate diagnosis and research.\r\n\r\nBy carefully examining each organ and its anatomical structures, such as blood vessels, tissues, and cellular components, Virchow's technique enables the pathologist to identify and analyze specific lesions, tumors, inflammatory changes, and other abnormalities. This detailed examination helps in establishing the cause of death, understanding the underlying disease processes, and providing valuable information for clinical management, research, and teaching purposes.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 103","responses":[{"text":"Each organ can be studied in detail","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Preservation of anatomico-pathologic relationship","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body can be made available to relatives in 30 minutes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preservation of vascular supply in pathological lesions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spread of infection (HIV, HCV) can be limited","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1926,"text":"If the cause of death can not be determined even after a thorough post mortem examination, toxicological analysis and histopathological examination, what is the autopsy called?","explanation":"The autopsy conducted when the cause of death cannot be determined even after a thorough post-mortem examination, toxicological analysis, and histopathological examination is called a **negative autopsy**. Despite comprehensive investigations, the specific cause or mechanism of death remains elusive in such cases.\r\n\r\nA negative autopsy can be challenging for both the pathologist and the investigating authorities, as the absence of a clear cause of death may hinder further legal proceedings, insurance claims, or closure for the deceased person's family. It highlights the limitations of current diagnostic techniques and emphasizes the need for continued research and advancements in forensic medicine and pathology.\r\n\r\nIn a negative autopsy, the pathologist provides a detailed report documenting the comprehensive investigations undertaken and the findings observed during the examination. This report helps establish that all possible avenues were explored to determine the cause of death, even if it ultimately remained unknown.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 116.","responses":[{"text":"Unusual autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Virtual autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incorrect autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Negative autopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Failure in autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2071,"text":"A 16-year-old tall male comes with sudden shortness of breath while he is playing football. His examination reveals, decreased air entry, hyper resonant percussion note with absent breath sound on the left side of the chest. Which of the following chest X-ray views should be requested to assess the lung pathology?","explanation":"The most appropriate view to evaluate the lung pathology in this case is the **expiratory posteroanterior (P/A) view**.\r\n\r\nThe expiratory P/A view is specifically performed to demonstrate air trapping or a large pneumothorax. It is obtained by taking an X-ray while the patient is instructed to exhale fully. This helps to accentuate the collapsed lung and visualize any air accumulation in the pleural space.\r\n\r\nBy comparing the expiratory P/A view with the normal P/A view, the extent of lung collapse and the presence of any associated complications, such as tension pneumothorax or pneumomediastinum, can be assessed.","reference":"1) Kelly B. The chest radiograph. Ulster Med J. 2012;81(3):143-148. Accessed May 20, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3632825/\r\n\r\n2) Masood I, Elyassi W, Rind W. Medicine. 3rd ed. Majeed Sons; 2018: 233.","responses":[{"text":"Chest X-Ray P/A view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inspiratory A/P view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Later decubitus view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Expiratory P/A view","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior A/P view","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2096,"text":"A 54-year-old man with a 20-pack year smoking history presents with shortness of breath. On physical examination, he is a thin and cyanotic man in moderate pulmonary distress. His chest shows an increased anteroposterior diameter, and breath sounds are faint with prolonged expiration. Which parameter is most likely found on the pulmonary function tests?","explanation":"In a 54-year-old man with a smoking history and symptoms of shortness of breath, the most likely finding on pulmonary function tests would be a **decreased FEV1: FVC ratio**. \r\n\r\nThe FEV1 (forced expiratory volume in 1 second) measures the amount of air that can be forcefully exhaled in the first second of a forced breath. The FVC (forced vital capacity) measures the total amount of air that can be forcefully exhaled after a maximal inhalation. \r\n\r\nIn obstructive lung diseases, such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), there is an obstruction of airflow, usually due to narrowing of the airways. This results in a decreased FEV1: FVC ratio, as the narrowing of the airways causes a reduction in the ability to forcefully exhale air in the first second.\r\n\r\nThe increased anteroposterior diameter of the chest, faint breath sounds, and prolonged expiration seen in the patient suggest the presence of emphysema, which is a common type of COPD.","reference":"1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 89.\r\n\r\n 2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 674.","responses":[{"text":"Increased FEV1: FVC ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased FEV1: FVC ratio","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deceased total lung capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal FEV1: FVC ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased forced vital capacity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2384,"text":"A 54-year-old diabetic patient came with complaints of fever and cough for the past three days. Chest X-Ray shows a consolidation on the right upper chest. Which of the following is a bad prognostic sign in this condition?","explanation":"In a diabetic patient presenting with fever and cough accompanied by a consolidation on the chest X-ray, a **respiratory rate greater than 30 breaths per minute is a bad prognostic sign**. An increased respiratory rate, also known as tachypnea, indicates respiratory distress and can be indicative of severe lung involvement or respiratory compromise.\r\n\r\nTachypnea is often associated with conditions such as pneumonia, including bacterial pneumonia, which can be a complication in diabetic patients. The rapid breathing is an attempt by the body to compensate for impaired gas exchange and to maintain adequate oxygenation.\r\n\r\nA high respiratory rate suggests significant lung involvement and respiratory compromise, which may require more aggressive management and close monitoring. It indicates a greater degree of respiratory distress and can be associated with a higher risk of respiratory failure and poor outcomes.","reference":"Strauß R, Ewig S, Richter K, König T, Heller G, T. Bauer T. The prognostic significance of respiratory rate in patients with pneumonia. Deutsches Ärzteblatt International. Published July 2014. Accessed May 20, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4150027/","responses":[{"text":"Respiratory rate \u003c 15","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory rate \u003c 30","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory rate \u003e 30","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory rate normal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal urea","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2386,"text":"A medico-legal doctor was called by the state law authorities to perform an autopsy on a suspected poisoning case. A detailed study of the stomach and its contents is usually done by which of the following?","explanation":"In a medico-legal autopsy, when a suspected poisoning case is being investigated, a detailed study of the stomach and its contents is usually done by **opening along the greater curvature**. \r\n\r\nOpening the stomach along the greater curvature allows for a thorough examination of the stomach's contents, including any ingested substances or potential toxicants. This approach provides a larger and more accessible area for examination and sampling of the stomach contents.\r\n\r\nBy opening along the greater curvature, the forensic pathologist can carefully inspect the contents, document any abnormalities, and collect samples for further analysis, such as toxicological testing. This technique ensures a comprehensive evaluation of the stomach, aiding in the identification of potential poisoning or other related pathological findings.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 104.","responses":[{"text":"Opening by a transverse incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening by incision on its anterior wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Can be opened by any side","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening along the greater curvature","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening along the lesser curvature","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2387,"text":"A 9-month-old child is brought to the clinic for the assessment of cough. On examination, his respiratory rate (R/R) is 52 breaths/minute with no chest retractions and no wheeze on auscultation. How will this child be classified according to Integrated Management of Newborn and Childhood Illnesses (IMNCI)?","explanation":"A 9-month-old child presenting with a cough and a respiratory rate of 52 breaths per minute is consistent with the Integrated Management of Newborn and Childhood Illnesses (IMNCI) guidelines for **pneumonia** assessment. The IMNCI guidelines consider a fast breathing rate (50 breaths per minute or more) in children under 12 months as an important indicator of pneumonia. In addition, the absence of chest retractions and wheezing suggests a milder form of pneumonia.\r\n\r\nAccording to the IMNCI classification, the child's presentation would be categorized as \"Pneumonia.\" This classification is based on the presence of a cough and a fast breathing rate, which are key symptoms considered in the IMNCI guidelines for respiratory illnesses in children.","reference":"INTEGRATED MANAGEMENT OF NEONATAL \u0026 CHILDHOOD ILLNESS. Published 2017. https://phkh.nhsrc.pk/sites/default/files/2020-02/IMNCI%20Chartbooklet%20Pakistan%202017.pdf","responses":[{"text":"Very severe disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cough and cold","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2390,"text":"In a putrefied body death resulted from drowning, diatoms are found in which of the following organs/viscera?","explanation":"In cases of death resulting from drowning, the presence of diatoms in specific organs/viscera can be helpful in establishing the cause of death. Diatoms are microscopic aquatic organisms that can enter the body during submersion in water and become trapped in various tissues.\r\n\r\nThe correct answer is **Brain and bone marrow**. Diatoms can be found in the brain and bone marrow due to their high vascularity and ability to accumulate diatoms during the drowning process. The presence of diatoms in these tissues provides strong evidence supporting death by drowning.\r\n\r\n- Hilum of right lung and right ear: While diatoms can enter the respiratory system during drowning, they are not typically found in the hilum of the lung or the ear.\r\n- Stomach and left lung: Diatoms are not commonly found in the stomach or the left lung.\r\n- Gall bladder and liver: Diatoms do not typically accumulate in the gall bladder or the liver.\r\n- Ileum and under surface of liver: These locations are not known to be associated with diatom accumulation in cases of drowning.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 182.","responses":[{"text":"Stomach and left lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileum and under surface of liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hilum of right lung and right ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brain and bone marrow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gall bladder and liver","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2400,"text":"If pulmonary function test shows FEV1/FVC ratio is more than 0.70 with decreased total lung capacity (TLC), then the interpretation would be:","explanation":"Interpreting pulmonary function tests involves assessing different parameters to identify patterns and abnormalities in lung function. In this case, a decreased total lung capacity (TLC) along with an FEV1/FVC ratio of more than 0.70 indicates a **restrictive pattern**. A restrictive lung disease is characterized by reduced lung volumes and limited expansion of the lungs.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 699.","responses":[{"text":"Non-specific reductions in FEV1 and FVC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive pattern","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed pattern","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive pattern","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2404,"text":"Tuberculosis granuloma of the lung exhibits characteristic features. Which of the following type of necrosis is seen in tuberculosis?","explanation":"The type of necrosis seen in tuberculosis granulomas of the lung is **caseous necrosis**. Caseous necrosis is a distinctive form of necrosis characterized by a cheesy, friable appearance of the affected tissue. In tuberculosis, it occurs as a result of the immune response to the Mycobacterium tuberculosis infection.\r\n\r\nDuring the course of tuberculosis infection, the immune system attempts to contain the bacteria by forming granulomas, which are aggregates of immune cells. Within these granulomas, the central area undergoes caseous necrosis. The necrotic material appears as a soft, friable, yellow-white cheese-like substance, giving it the name \"caseous.\"\r\n\r\nThe presence of caseous necrosis in tuberculosis granulomas is a hallmark feature of the disease and can be visualized on histological examination of lung tissue. It is an important diagnostic clue for tuberculosis and helps differentiate it from other types of necrosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 98.","responses":[{"text":"Hyaline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseous","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liquefactive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coagulative","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2410,"text":"Which of the following agents can reverse the peripheral neuropathy caused by isoniazid?","explanation":"The agent that can reverse the peripheral neuropathy caused by isoniazid is **pyridoxine** (vitamin B6). Isoniazid is an antituberculosis medication that can lead to peripheral neuropathy as a side effect. This occurs due to the depletion of pyridoxine, which is a cofactor for several enzymes involved in neurotransmitter synthesis and nerve function.\r\n\r\nSupplementing with pyridoxine helps prevent and reverse the peripheral neuropathy associated with isoniazid therapy. Pyridoxine acts by replenishing the deficient levels of vitamin B6, which is necessary for maintaining the normal functioning of the peripheral nerves.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that the use of pyridoxine as a preventive or therapeutic measure for isoniazid-induced peripheral neuropathy is recommended for individuals at high risk, such as those with diabetes, malnutrition, alcoholism, or pregnant women.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 841.","responses":[{"text":"Thiamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Niacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascorbic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyridoxine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Folate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2455,"text":"A 21-year-old female came with a dry cough and shortness of breath for 6 months. For the past week, she is also having nocturnal symptoms. Her treating physician advised a pulmonary function test. \r\nInterpret the following pulmonary function test of this lady: FEV1=50% of predicted, FEV1/FVC=60%, and FVC=82% of predicted.","explanation":"The interpretation of the pulmonary function test (PFT) results for this 21-year-old female shows **an obstructive pattern**. \r\n\r\nThe key parameters to consider are the **FEV1** (forced expiratory volume in 1 second), **FEV1/FVC** (forced expiratory volume in 1 second to forced vital capacity ratio), and **FVC** (forced vital capacity). In this case, the FEV1 is significantly reduced (50% of predicted), indicating airflow limitation. The FEV1/FVC ratio is also decreased (60%), further supporting the presence of airflow obstruction. The FVC is relatively preserved (82% of predicted), indicating that the patient's total lung capacity is not significantly reduced.\r\n\r\nThese findings are consistent with an **obstructive pattern**, suggesting the presence of conditions such as **chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)** or **asthma**. The reduced FEV1 indicates impaired airflow, and the decreased FEV1/FVC ratio indicates a limitation in expiratory airflow compared to the total lung capacity.","reference":"1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 89.\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n  2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 674.","responses":[{"text":"Normal pulmonary function test (PFT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive pattern","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Poor effort","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed pattern","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive pattern","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2570,"text":"Which one of the following is an external sign of antemortem hanging in case of instantaneous death?","explanation":"The external sign of antemortem hanging that is indicative of instantaneous death is **tongue protrusion with saliva dribbling from the mouth**.\r\n\r\nDuring hanging, the constriction of the ligature around the neck can cause pressure on the structures within the throat, leading to obstruction of the airway and subsequent asphyxiation. In cases of instantaneous death, the individual may not have had the opportunity to close their mouth or swallow, resulting in the tongue protruding out of the mouth. Additionally, saliva may accumulate and dribble from the mouth due to the loss of control over the oral muscles.\r\n\r\nThe other options mentioned, such as hemorrhages in the lymph nodes above the ligature mark, bruising, rupture, or laceration of neck soft structures, face and head congestion, and congestion in the lymph nodes above and below the ligature mark, are not specific to instantaneous death and can also be observed in cases of both antemortem and postmortem hanging.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 164.","responses":[{"text":"Face and head above ligature may be congested","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bruising, rupture, or laceration of neck's soft structures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tongue protruding with saliva dribbling from the mouth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Congestion in the lymph nodes above and below ligature mark","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhages in the lymph nodes above the ligature mark","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2715,"text":"What is the best first-line diagnostic test for pulmonary embolism?","explanation":"The best first-line diagnostic test for pulmonary embolism is **computerized tomography (CT) pulmonary angiography**.\r\n\r\nPulmonary embolism (PE) occurs when a blood clot (thrombus) travels to the lungs and obstructs the pulmonary arteries. CT pulmonary angiography is the preferred initial diagnostic test for suspected PE due to its high sensitivity and specificity. It involves the injection of a contrast dye into a vein, followed by CT scanning of the pulmonary arteries. This imaging technique allows for the visualization of the blood vessels in the lungs and can identify the presence of a clot.\r\n\r\nOther diagnostic tests mentioned, such as chest x-ray, arterial blood gases, coagulation profile, and electrocardiography, may provide supportive information but are not considered first-line tests for confirming or ruling out pulmonary embolism. Chest x-ray may show nonspecific findings, while arterial blood gases and electrocardiography can indicate secondary changes due to compromised lung function. Coagulation profile may help evaluate the patient's overall coagulation status but is not specific to pulmonary embolism.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 620.","responses":[{"text":"Computerized tomography (CT) pulmonary angiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterial blood gases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest x-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electrocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coagulation profile","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2742,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding the dissection of the heart during autopsy?","explanation":"During the dissection of the heart in an autopsy, the correct approach is to **open the heart in the direction of blood** flow. This means that the dissection starts from the atria and progresses to the ventricles, following the path of blood flow through the heart.\r\n\r\nOpening the heart in the direction of blood flow allows for a systematic examination of the internal structures and chambers, ensuring a thorough assessment of any abnormalities or pathological changes. By following the natural flow of blood, the pathologist can observe the valves, assess the thickness of the myocardium, inspect the coronary arteries, and examine the internal structures of the heart in a logical sequence.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 106.","responses":[{"text":"The ventricle is opened first, followed by the atrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opposite to the direction of blood flow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Both chambers are opened together","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The direction and order does not matter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In the direction of blood flow","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10287,"text":"Which of the following drugs acts as a controller in the management of an asthma attack?","explanation":"In the management of an asthma attack, **inhaled corticosteroids** are an essential component for controlling inflammation and reducing airway hyperresponsiveness. Asthma is characterized by chronic airway inflammation, and inhaled corticosteroids work by reducing this inflammation in the airways.\r\n\r\nInhaled corticosteroids have anti-inflammatory properties and help to suppress the immune response in the airways, reducing the production of inflammatory mediators and the recruitment of inflammatory cells. They also help to prevent the release of substances that can cause bronchoconstriction.\r\n\r\nUnlike short-acting beta agonists, which provide quick relief by relaxing the bronchial smooth muscle during an acute asthma attack, inhaled corticosteroids have a longer-term effect and are used as controllers or maintenance medications to prevent asthma symptoms and reduce the frequency and severity of asthma attacks.\r\n\r\nBy reducing airway inflammation and improving overall asthma control, inhaled corticosteroids help to prevent exacerbations and maintain long-term respiratory function in individuals with asthma.","reference":"Medication for people with asthma. Published November 30, 2017. Accessed May 19, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279519/","responses":[{"text":"Anti-cholinergics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Theophylline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short-acting beta agonists","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhaled corticosteroids","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta 2 agonists","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10366,"text":"Hypercalcemia is the paraneoplastic syndrome associated with which of the following underlying cancers?","explanation":"Hypercalcemia is a paraneoplastic syndrome that can occur in various types of cancer, but it is most commonly associated with **squamous cell carcinoma of the lung**. Paraneoplastic syndromes are a group of clinical manifestations that are not directly related to the local effects of the tumor but arise as a result of tumor-secreted products or an immune response to the tumor.\r\n\r\nIn squamous cell carcinoma of the lung, tumor cells can produce parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP), which shares structural similarity with parathyroid hormone (PTH) and can bind to PTH receptors. PTHrP can stimulate bone resorption, leading to an increase in calcium release from the bone and subsequent hypercalcemia.\r\n\r\nHypercalcemia can cause a variety of clinical manifestations, including fatigue, weakness, anorexia, constipation, kidney stones, and altered mental status. Prompt identification and management of the underlying cause of hypercalcemia are important to prevent complications and improve patient outcomes.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 719.","responses":[{"text":"Ovarian carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma of lung","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Large cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small cell carcinoma of lungs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10414,"text":"Which of the following statements is true about respiratory failure?","explanation":"Respiratory failure is a condition characterized by the inability of the respiratory system to adequately oxygenate the blood or remove carbon dioxide. It is classified into two types: type I and type II respiratory failure.\r\n\r\nType I respiratory failure, also known as hypoxemic respiratory failure, is characterized by low oxygen levels (hypoxemia) in the blood while the carbon dioxide levels remain normal or low. It typically occurs due to impaired gas exchange in the lungs, such as in conditions like pneumonia, acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), or pulmonary embolism.\r\n\r\nType II respiratory failure, also known as hypercapnic respiratory failure, is characterized by **low oxygen levels along with high carbon dioxide levels** (hypercapnia) in the blood. This type of respiratory failure is commonly seen in conditions where there is a decreased ability to ventilate or remove carbon dioxide from the lungs, such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) or severe asthma.\r\n\r\nHypoxemia refers to a low level of oxygen in the blood, and hypercapnia refers to a high level of carbon dioxide in the blood. These terms are used to describe specific abnormalities in blood gas levels rather than overall respiratory failure.","reference":"Shebl E, Burns B. Respiratory failure. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526127/","responses":[{"text":"Type II respiratory failure involves normal oxygen and high carbon dioxide levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type I respiratory failure involves low oxygen and high carbon dioxide levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type II respiratory failure involves low oxygen and high carbon dioxide levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A high level of oxygen in the blood is known as hypoxemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A low level of carbon dioxide in the blood is known as hypercapnea","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10416,"text":"A 69-year-old man presented to the outpatient department with complaints of chronic fatigue for the last 15 months. He has had a history of hypertension for many years. On examination, he is afebrile. Chest x-ray shows bilateral pulmonary edema with a prominent border on the left side of the heart. What is the probable diagnosis of this case?","explanation":"**Concentric hypertrophy** is a cardiac condition characterized by an increase in the thickness of the left ventricular wall, particularly the myocardium. It commonly occurs as a result of long-standing hypertension, which imposes an increased workload on the heart.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the patient has a history of hypertension for many years, which is a risk factor for the development of concentric hypertrophy. The increased thickness of the left ventricular wall can lead to impaired diastolic function and decreased compliance of the heart, resulting in elevated left atrial pressures and subsequent pulmonary congestion. The prominent border on the left side of the heart seen on the chest X-ray is indicative of left ventricular enlargement.\r\n\r\nOther conditions such as dilated cardiomyopathy or hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy may also cause heart failure and pulmonary edema, but the history of long-standing hypertension in this patient makes concentric hypertrophy more likely.","reference":"Aronow WS. Hypertension and left ventricular hypertrophy. Annals of Translational Medicine. Published August 2017. Accessed May 19, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5555990/","responses":[{"text":"Concentric hypertrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Eccentric hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal heart","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10417,"text":"A 58-year-old man presented to the outpatient department with complaints of abdominal pain and swelling in the lower limb for two years. On examination, he has raised jugular venous pressure even upon sitting. The liver is enlarged and tender. Pitting edema can be observed in the lower extremities Chest radiograph shows pleural effusion and increased lucency of the lung field. What is the probable diagnosis of this case?","explanation":"**Right-sided heart failure** occurs when the right ventricle is unable to effectively pump blood to the lungs, leading to congestion and fluid accumulation in the systemic venous circulation.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with right-sided heart failure. The raised jugular venous pressure, hepatomegaly, and pitting edema in the lower extremities are all indicative of increased venous pressure and fluid retention in the systemic circulation. The presence of pleural effusion and increased lucency of the lung field on the chest radiograph suggests pulmonary congestion and compromised lung function.\r\n\r\nLeft-sided heart failure, on the other hand, typically manifests with symptoms such as dyspnea, orthopnea, and pulmonary edema. However, in this case, the clinical findings are more consistent with right-sided heart failure, indicating that the right side of the heart is primarily affected.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 318.","responses":[{"text":"Right-sided heart failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left-sided heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10418,"text":"A 60-year-old man presented to the outpatient department with the complaint of onset of sudden substernal chest pain when performing exertional tasks. The pain has increased in frequency over the past year. On examination, he was afebrile, his heart rate was 78 bpm, and his heartbeat was regular, with no murmurs or gallops. What is the probable diagnosis of this case?","explanation":"**Angina pectoris** is characterized by chest pain or discomfort that occurs when there is an inadequate blood supply to the heart muscle. It is typically triggered by exertion or emotional stress and relieved by rest or nitroglycerin.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the patient's sudden substernal chest pain during exertional tasks, along with the increasing frequency of the pain over time, is consistent with the clinical presentation of angina pectoris. The absence of fever, regular heartbeat, and absence of murmurs or gallops on examination further support this diagnosis.\r\n\r\nIt is important to differentiate angina pectoris from myocardial infarction, which presents with similar symptoms but is characterized by the presence of myocardial cell death and elevation of cardiac biomarkers.\r\n\r\nFurther diagnostic evaluation, such as an electrocardiogram (ECG) and stress test, may be necessary to confirm the diagnosis of angina pectoris and determine the appropriate management approach.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 539.","responses":[{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left-sided heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinous pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angina pectoris","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10419,"text":"Which of the following is the best management for quick relief of acute asthma?","explanation":"The best management for quick relief of acute asthma is the use of **inhaled beta-2 agonists**. Beta-2 agonists act on the beta-2 adrenergic receptors in the airway smooth muscles, leading to bronchodilation and relieving acute bronchoconstriction in asthma.\r\n\r\nInhaled beta-2 agonists are considered the first-line treatment for acute asthma exacerbations due to their rapid onset of action and effectiveness in relieving symptoms. They are available in short-acting formulations, such as albuterol or salbutamol, which provide quick relief when inhaled directly into the lungs.\r\n\r\nAnticholinergics, systemic glucocorticoids, inhaled glucocorticoids, and theophylline are also important components of asthma management but are more commonly used for long-term control and prevention of asthma symptoms rather than for quick relief during acute exacerbations.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 529.","responses":[{"text":"Systemic glucocorticoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Theophylline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhaled beta-2 agonists","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anticholinergic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhaled glucocorticoids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10420,"text":"All of the following factors exacerbate chronic obstructive pulmonary disease except which one?","explanation":"**Oxygen therapy** is not an exacerbating factor for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD); in fact, it is an important treatment modality for patients with advanced COPD and chronic hypoxemia. Oxygen therapy helps improve oxygenation and relieve symptoms in patients with COPD who have low oxygen levels in their blood.\r\n\r\nThe other factors listed—smoking, airway hyperresponsiveness, infection, and pollutant exposure—can exacerbate COPD. Smoking is the leading cause of COPD and continued smoking can worsen the disease progression. Airway hyperresponsiveness refers to the increased sensitivity of the airways to various triggers, which can lead to bronchoconstriction and exacerbations. Infections, particularly respiratory infections such as pneumonia, can cause acute exacerbations of COPD. Exposure to pollutants, such as environmental pollutants or occupational toxins, can also worsen symptoms and lung function in individuals with COPD.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 679.","responses":[{"text":"Smoking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen therapy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pollutant exposure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Airway hyperresponsiveness","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10422,"text":"Which of the following factors is not included in the disciples of ergonomics?","explanation":"**Ergonomics** is the science of designing and arranging work environments and systems to optimize human performance and well-being. It aims to reduce the risk of musculoskeletal injuries, improve productivity, and enhance overall comfort and efficiency in the workplace. While nutrition is an important aspect of maintaining good health, it is not typically considered a primary factor within the discipline of ergonomics.\r\n\r\nThe disciples of ergonomics primarily focus on factors directly related to the work environment and the interaction between workers and their tasks. This includes considerations such as the design of machines and equipment, layout of the workplace, proper lighting, noise control, work posture, and movement. Additionally, ergonomics may address issues related to workload, work organization, and employee training.\r\n\r\nAlthough **nutrition** indirectly impacts overall health and well-being, it is not typically within the scope of ergonomics. However, promoting a healthy lifestyle, including good nutrition, may be encouraged as part of a broader occupational health and wellness program.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Flexible work schedule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutrition","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Work environment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Layout of the workplace","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Machine design","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10424,"text":"What is the concentration of oxygen in air?","explanation":"The concentration of oxygen in the air is approximately **20.9%**. The Earth's atmosphere is composed of various gases, with oxygen being one of the most important for supporting life. In the atmosphere, oxygen exists as diatomic oxygen molecules (O2). This concentration of oxygen is considered optimal for normal respiratory function and is necessary for sustaining human and animal life.\r\n\r\nIt's worth noting that the remaining composition of air primarily consists of nitrogen (approximately 78%) and traces of other gases such as carbon dioxide, argon, and water vapor. These gases play important roles in various physiological and environmental processes.","reference":"Wuthichotwanichgij G, Geater AF. Low-oxygen atmosphere and its predictors among agricultural shallow wells in northern thailand. Safety and Health at Work. Published March 2015. Accessed June 14, 2023. https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S2093791114000808","responses":[{"text":"0.0325%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20.9%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"78%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.25%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"61%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10425,"text":"A 20-year-old African American female presented to the outpatient department with the complaint of shortness of breath. Chest x-ray shows bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy. What is the probable diagnosis?","explanation":"**Sarcoidosis** is a multisystem disorder characterized by the formation of non-caseating granulomas in various organs, most commonly the lungs and hilar lymph nodes. It predominantly affects young adults, particularly individuals of African American descent.\r\n\r\nThe hallmark feature of sarcoidosis is the presence of granulomas, which are aggregates of activated immune cells, particularly macrophages, in affected tissues. These granulomas can cause inflammation and organ dysfunction. In the lungs, the presence of bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy is a classic finding, indicating involvement of the mediastinal lymph nodes.\r\n\r\nSarcoidosis can have a variable clinical presentation, ranging from asymptomatic to severe respiratory symptoms, depending on the extent and severity of organ involvement. Other common manifestations include pulmonary infiltrates, skin lesions, ocular abnormalities, and systemic symptoms such as fatigue and weight loss.\r\n\r\nFurther diagnostic evaluation may include biopsy of affected tissues, pulmonary function tests, and assessment of other organ systems to establish the diagnosis and determine the extent of the disease. Treatment is based on the severity and organ involvement, and may include corticosteroids and other immunosuppressive agents. Regular monitoring is essential to assess disease activity and manage potential complications.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 696.","responses":[{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesothelioma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histoplasmosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10426,"text":"Which of the following factors increase the incidence of pneumoconiosis in coal-mine workers?","explanation":"The incidence of pneumoconiosis in coal-mine workers is primarily influenced by the **concentration of dust in the air and the duration of exposure to coal mine dust**. Pneumoconiosis refers to a group of lung diseases caused by the inhalation of mineral dust particles, with coal workers' pneumoconiosis specifically affecting coal miners.\r\n\r\nCoal mine workers are exposed to high levels of coal mine dust containing coal particles and other mineral components. The concentration of dust in the air is a critical factor as it determines the amount of dust that workers inhale. Prolonged exposure to high levels of coal mine dust increases the risk of developing pneumoconiosis.\r\n\r\nThe size of the particles inhaled can also contribute to the development of pneumoconiosis. Fine particles have a greater ability to penetrate deep into the lungs and cause damage.\r\n\r\nThe worker's physical condition, such as pre-existing respiratory conditions or compromised lung function, can influence the susceptibility and severity of pneumoconiosis but may not directly increase the incidence.\r\n\r\nOther factors such as the use of personal protective equipment, dust control measures, and workplace ventilation can help reduce dust exposure and consequently the incidence of pneumoconiosis in coal-mine workers. Regular monitoring, early detection, and appropriate management are essential in the prevention and control of this occupational lung disease.","reference":"Han L, Han R, Ji X, et al. Prevalence characteristics of coal workers’ pneumoconiosis (Cwp) in a state-owned mine in eastern china. Int J Environ Res Public Health. 2015;12(7):7856-7867. doi:10.3390/ijerph120707856","responses":[{"text":"Worker's physical condition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Concentration of dust in air","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duration of exposure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Concentration of dust in air and duration of exposure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Size of particles inhaled","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10447,"text":"Based on which of the following factors can extrinsic asthma be diagnosed?","explanation":"Extrinsic asthma, also known as allergic asthma, can be diagnosed based on the presence of raised IgE (immunoglobulin E) levels. IgE is an antibody produced by the immune system in response to exposure to allergens. In allergic asthma, the immune system overreacts to certain triggers, such as pollen, dust mites, or pet dander, leading to inflammation and narrowing of the airways.\r\n\r\nMeasuring IgE levels through a blood test can help identify individuals with allergic asthma. Elevated IgE levels indicate an increased sensitivity to specific allergens and support the diagnosis of extrinsic asthma. However, it is important to note that the diagnosis of asthma is multifactorial, and clinical evaluation, including a detailed history of symptoms, physical examination, and lung function tests, is also crucial.\r\n\r\nOther factors, such as a patient's history of respiratory symptoms triggered by allergens, response to allergen-specific testing, and improvement with appropriate asthma medications, also contribute to the diagnosis of extrinsic asthma.","reference":"Extrinsic vs. Intrinsic asthma: the main differences. Pulmonary Associates of Brandon. Accessed May 20, 2022. https://floridachest.com/pulmonary-blog/extrinsic-vs-intrinsic-asthma-the-main-differences","responses":[{"text":"Raised IgG levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised white blood cell count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"On the basis of history","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest x-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised IgE levels","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10454,"text":"Which of the following techniques is used to find trace elements in postmortem examination?","explanation":"**Neutron activation analysis** is a technique used to detect and measure trace elements in postmortem examination. This method involves exposing the sample to a neutron beam, which causes the atoms within the sample to become radioactive. The radioactive isotopes emit characteristic gamma rays that can be detected and analyzed to determine the presence and concentration of specific elements.\r\n\r\nIn forensic toxicology and postmortem examinations, neutron activation analysis is particularly useful for identifying and quantifying trace elements, such as heavy metals, in various tissues and body fluids. These elements may be important in cases involving poisoning, environmental exposures, or occupational hazards.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 229.","responses":[{"text":"Blood test for drug detection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutron activation analysis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultraviolet lamp","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography scan","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10457,"text":"Which of the following findings in a body confirms death by drowning upon postmortem examination?","explanation":"The presence of **diatoms in the brain and kidney** is a significant finding in postmortem examination that confirms death by drowning. Diatoms are microscopic aquatic algae that can be inhaled or ingested by an individual when submerged in water. During drowning, these diatoms can enter the bloodstream and settle in various organs, including the brain and kidney.\r\n\r\nDiatom analysis involves the microscopic examination of these algae in tissue samples obtained during autopsy. The presence of diatoms in the brain and kidney suggests that the individual was alive at the time of submersion and inhaled or ingested water, leading to drowning.\r\n\r\nOther findings such as oronasal froth, ballooning or voluminous lungs, and cutis anserina (goosebumps) can also be associated with drowning but are not specific to drowning alone.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 202.","responses":[{"text":"Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ballooning or voluminous lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oronasal froth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cutis anserina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diatoms in brain and kidney","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10459,"text":"The mechanism of action of cromolyn prevents the release of mediators and includes which of the following?","explanation":"The mechanism of action of cromolyn involves the prevention of the release of mediators, particularly from mast cells. It is used in the management of asthma and other allergic conditions. \r\n\r\nCromolyn works by stabilizing mast cells, which are involved in the immune response and release various inflammatory mediators such as histamine, leukotrienes, and prostaglandins. By stabilizing mast cells, cromolyn prevents the release of these mediators, thereby reducing the inflammatory response in the airways.\r\n\r\nThis mechanism of action helps to prevent bronchoconstriction and inflammation in the airways, leading to the **relaxation of bronchial smooth muscle**. It does not directly affect leukocytes, muscarinic receptors, beta-adrenergic receptors, or phosphodiesterase activity.\r\n\r\nBy inhibiting the release of mediators, cromolyn helps to control asthma symptoms and prevent asthma attacks. It is typically administered via inhalation to target the airways directly.","reference":"Minutello K, Gupta V. Cromolyn sodium. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 20, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557473/","responses":[{"text":"Relaxation of bronchial smooth muscle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of beta-adrenergic receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of leukocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockage of muscarinic receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of phosphodiesterase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10460,"text":"Which beta-blocker drugs is contraindicated in asthma?","explanation":"**Propranolol** is contraindicated in asthma due to its non-selective beta-blocking activity, which can cause bronchoconstriction and worsen asthma symptoms. Propranolol blocks both beta-1 and beta-2 adrenergic receptors, leading to the constriction of bronchial smooth muscle and a decrease in bronchodilation. This can result in airway narrowing and exacerbation of respiratory symptoms in patients with asthma.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, other beta-blockers such as atenolol, metoprolol, and esmolol have selective beta-1 blocking activity, which primarily affects the heart and has less impact on the bronchial smooth muscle. Therefore, these selective beta-blockers are considered safer for use in patients with asthma, as they are less likely to cause bronchoconstriction.\r\n\r\nSalbutamol, on the other hand, is a short-acting beta-2 adrenergic agonist commonly used in the treatment of asthma. It works by relaxing bronchial smooth muscle and promoting bronchodilation.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 94-95.","responses":[{"text":"Salbutamol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoprolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atenolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propanolol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esmolol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11716,"text":"What is the most common cause of community-acquired atypical pneumonia in older children?","explanation":"**_Mycoplasma pneumoniae_** is the most common cause of community-acquired atypical pneumonia in older children. It is considered atypical because it presents with a different clinical picture compared to typical bacterial pneumonia caused by organisms like Streptococcus pneumoniae.\r\n\r\nMycoplasma pneumoniae typically affects older children and young adults and is more common in crowded settings such as schools and dormitories. It is characterized by a gradual onset of symptoms including non-productive cough, sore throat, headache, malaise, and low-grade fever. Chest X-ray findings often reveal patchy infiltrates or consolidation.\r\n\r\nOther causes of community-acquired atypical pneumonia include respiratory viruses like influenza, bacterial pathogens such as Legionella pneumophila and Chlamydophila pneumoniae, and certain fungi.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 88.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycoplasma pneumoniae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Influenza virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilus influenza","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11717,"text":"A 36-year-old male is on anti-tuberculosis therapy (ATT) including isoniazid for 4 weeks. He now presents to the clinic with paresthesia and tingling sensation in his hands and feet. Which of the following is likely to be the cause of this?","explanation":"The likely cause of paresthesia and tingling sensation in the hands and feet in this patient receiving anti-tuberculosis therapy (ATT) is **peripheral neuritis**. Peripheral neuritis refers to inflammation of the peripheral nerves, and it can be a side effect of isoniazid, which is commonly used in ATT regimens for tuberculosis.\r\n\r\nIsoniazid is known to cause peripheral neuropathy, particularly due to its effect on vitamin B6 (pyridoxine) metabolism. Isoniazid can lead to pyridoxine deficiency, which is essential for nerve function and maintenance. The deficiency of pyridoxine can result in nerve damage, leading to symptoms such as paresthesia, tingling, and sensory disturbances in the hands and feet.\r\n\r\nTo prevent or manage peripheral neuritis associated with isoniazid therapy, it is recommended to supplement with pyridoxine (vitamin B6) concurrently. This helps to counteract the deficiency and reduce the risk of nerve damage.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 403.","responses":[{"text":"Nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatotoxicity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinary tract infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral neuritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal cord compression","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11718,"text":"In a body that has been hanged, the constriction force is generated by which of the following?","explanation":"In a hanging, the constriction force is generated by the **weight of the body**. When a person is hanged, the weight of their body pulls down on the noose or ligature, creating pressure around the neck. This pressure causes compression and obstruction of the blood vessels and airways in the neck, leading to asphyxia.\r\n\r\nThe weight of the body acts as the force that tightens the ligature and creates the constriction necessary to block the blood flow and airflow. The severity of the constriction depends on factors such as the weight of the individual and the type of ligature used.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Respiratory module, Community medicine slides, Topic: Asphyxia II.","responses":[{"text":"Position of the knot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Height of the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight of the rope","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight of the body","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11719,"text":"Which of the following is a potent and non-specific bronchodilator which can not be given orally?","explanation":"**Epinephrine**, also known as adrenaline, is a naturally occurring hormone and neurotransmitter that plays a vital role in the body's response to stress and emergency situations.\r\n\r\nWhen used as a bronchodilator, epinephrine acts on the beta-2 adrenergic receptors in the smooth muscles of the airways. It relaxes the bronchial smooth muscles, leading to bronchodilation and improved airflow. This helps relieve symptoms of bronchospasm and respiratory distress in conditions such as asthma and acute allergic reactions.\r\n\r\nDue to its poor oral bioavailability and rapid metabolism, epinephrine is typically administered via inhalation or injection routes. Inhalation of epinephrine through devices such as metered-dose inhalers or nebulizers allows for direct delivery to the lungs, providing rapid bronchodilation.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 342.","responses":[{"text":"Epinephrine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Terbutaline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoprolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ipratropium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cromolyn","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11720,"text":"Which of the following is also called sewer gas?","explanation":"**Hydrogen sulfide (H2S)** is commonly referred to as sewer gas. It is a colorless, highly toxic gas with a strong odor of rotten eggs. Hydrogen sulfide is produced naturally by the breakdown of organic matter in anaerobic conditions, such as in sewers, swamps, and other areas with decaying organic materials.\r\n\r\nExposure to hydrogen sulfide can occur in occupational settings, such as wastewater treatment plants, sewers, and industries involved in oil and gas refining. It can also occur in residential settings where plumbing or sewage systems are compromised.\r\n\r\nInhalation of hydrogen sulfide can cause various health effects, ranging from mild irritation to severe toxicity. Low-level exposure may lead to symptoms such as headache, dizziness, nausea, and eye irritation. Higher concentrations can result in respiratory distress, loss of consciousness, and even death.","reference":"PubChem. Hydrogen sulfide. Accessed May 20, 2022. https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/402","responses":[{"text":"CO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"O2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H2S","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"N2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11721,"text":"Multiple drugs are given in anti-tuberculosis therapy (ATT) because of which of the following reasons?","explanation":"Multiple drugs are used in anti-tuberculosis therapy (ATT) for the purpose of **preventing resistance against any drug**. Tuberculosis is caused by the bacterium Mycobacterium tuberculosis, which has a slow growth rate and can develop resistance to individual drugs over time. By using a combination of drugs, each with a different mechanism of action, the likelihood of the bacteria developing resistance is significantly reduced.\r\n\r\nThe use of multiple drugs in ATT also helps to provide a bactericidal effect and improve treatment outcomes. Different drugs target various stages of the bacterial life cycle, such as cell wall synthesis, protein synthesis, and nucleic acid synthesis, thereby increasing the effectiveness of treatment.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the use of multiple drugs helps to ensure complete eradication of the organism, as some drugs may be more effective against certain populations of bacteria than others. This reduces the risk of treatment failure and the development of drug-resistant strains.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, combining multiple drugs in a treatment regimen may improve patient compliance by simplifying the dosing schedule and reducing the overall duration of treatment.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 116.","responses":[{"text":"To completely eradicate the organism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To prevent resistance against any drug","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"To provide a bactericidal effect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To avoid side effects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To improve patient compliance","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11729,"text":"Compared to an abstract, a synopsis does not have which of the following?","explanation":"Compared to an abstract, a **synopsis does not typically include the results** of the study. A synopsis provides a concise summary of a research study or project, highlighting its key aspects and findings. While an abstract usually includes the main findings or results of a study, a synopsis focuses more on the background, objective, methods, and significance of the research. It serves as a brief overview or outline of the study, allowing readers to quickly grasp the main points without going into extensive detail.\r\n\r\nIn a synopsis, the introduction provides background information about the topic, the objective statement states the purpose of the study, the sample size describes the number of participants or subjects included, and the hypothesis presents the expected outcome or relationship being tested. However, the detailed results and statistical analyses are typically omitted from a synopsis, as it aims to provide a concise summary rather than a comprehensive report.","reference":"Difference between abstract and summary. Pediaa. Published January 8, 2016. Accessed May 10, 2022. https://pediaa.com/difference-between-abstract-and-summary/","responses":[{"text":"Result","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sample size","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Introduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Objective statement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11730,"text":"Non intrusive form of autopsy in which computed tomography (CT scan) and magnified resonance imaging (MRI) are used is known as?","explanation":"The non-intrusive form of autopsy that utilizes computed tomography (CT scan) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) is known as **virtopsy**. Virtopsy combines advanced imaging techniques with traditional forensic methods to perform a comprehensive examination of the body without the need for conventional autopsy procedures. It allows for detailed visualization and analysis of the internal structures, organs, and tissues, providing valuable information about the cause of death and any associated injuries or pathologies.\r\n\r\nVirtopsy offers several advantages over traditional autopsies, including the preservation of the body's integrity, non-destructiveness, and the ability to capture high-resolution images for further analysis. It can help in identifying traumatic injuries, detecting hidden internal injuries, assessing the extent of organ damage, and identifying abnormal findings that may have contributed to the cause of death. Additionally, virtopsy can aid in forensic investigations, providing valuable evidence in cases of homicide, accidents, and medical malpractice.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Respiratory module, Community medicine slides, Topic: Autopsy I.","responses":[{"text":"Virtopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Necropsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scan autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monitor autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ghost autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11731,"text":"Obscure autopsy results most commonly due to which of the following?","explanation":"Obscure autopsy results are most commonly due to **concealed trauma**, such as a concussion of the head. In some cases, there may be no visible external signs of injury, making it challenging to detect the cause of death or identify specific injuries during the external examination of the body. These concealed injuries can be internal and may require a thorough internal examination to uncover them.\r\n\r\nConcealed trauma, such as a head concussion, can result from various causes, including accidents, falls, or physical assaults. The absence of visible external signs of injury can make it difficult to initially suspect or detect such trauma during the external examination. However, a detailed internal examination, including examination of the skull, brain, and surrounding structures, can reveal the presence of hidden injuries and provide vital clues regarding the cause of death.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Respiratory module, Community medicine slides, Topic: Autopsy III.","responses":[{"text":"Improper internal examination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Concealed trauma such as concussion of head","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Poor knowledge of the prosector","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Improper external examination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incorrect report by the prosector","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11740,"text":"What is the mechanism of action of bromhexine?","explanation":"Bromhexine is an expectorant commonly used to help alleviate respiratory conditions associated with excessive mucus production, such as bronchitis and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). The mechanism of action of bromhexine involves **increasing mucus clearance** from the respiratory tract.\r\n\r\nBromhexine works by stimulating the activity of cilia, which are small hair-like structures lining the respiratory tract. The cilia play a vital role in moving mucus and trapped particles out of the airways. Bromhexine enhances the movement of cilia, thereby increasing the clearance of mucus and facilitating its expulsion from the lungs.\r\n\r\nBy promoting mucus clearance, bromhexine helps to reduce congestion, relieve cough, and improve respiratory symptoms. It does not inhibit or promote the cough reflex directly but rather facilitates the removal of excess mucus from the airways, which can help alleviate coughing associated with excessive mucus production.","reference":"PubChem. Bromhexine. Accessed May 10, 2022. https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/2442","responses":[{"text":"Promotes cough reflex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreases the production of serous mucus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases mucus clearance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreases mucus clearance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits cough reflex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11741,"text":"Which of the following contributes mainly to green house gas?","explanation":"**Carbon dioxide (CO2)** is the main contributor to greenhouse gas emissions. Greenhouse gases trap heat in the Earth's atmosphere, leading to the greenhouse effect and global warming. CO2 is released through various human activities, primarily the burning of fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas for energy production, transportation, and industrial processes.\r\n\r\nThe combustion of fossil fuels releases carbon that has been stored underground for millions of years, adding it to the carbon cycle and increasing the concentration of CO2 in the atmosphere. Deforestation also contributes to CO2 emissions, as trees play a crucial role in absorbing CO2 through photosynthesis.\r\n\r\nOther gases, such as methane (CH4), nitrous oxide (N2O), and fluorinated gases, also contribute to the greenhouse effect, but CO2 is the most significant and prevalent greenhouse gas. Efforts to reduce CO2 emissions and mitigate climate change include transitioning to renewable energy sources, improving energy efficiency, and implementing carbon capture and storage technologies.","reference":"Shakoor A, Ashraf F, Shakoor S, Mustafa A, Rehman A, Altaf MM. Biogeochemical transformation of greenhouse gas emissions from terrestrial to atmospheric environment and potential feedback to climate forcing. Environmental Science and Pollution Research International.","responses":[{"text":"H2S","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CO","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CH4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CO2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"N2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11775,"text":"A 7-year-old boy decides to put beads in his mouth to blow out on his sister but he accidentally aspirates the beads. One day later, he develops dyspnea, a temperature of 98.4 F, decreased breath sounds and a dull percussion note over the right lobe. Sputum shows normal flora. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"Atelectasis refers to the collapse or closure of a part or the entire lung. **Resorptive atelectasis** occurs when an obstructive lesion, such as a foreign body, blocks a bronchus and prevents the ventilation of the affected lung segment or lobe.\r\n\r\nIn this scenario, the aspiration of beads by the 7-year-old boy has led to the obstruction of a bronchus in the right lobe of the lung. The subsequent lack of ventilation in the affected area causes the alveoli to collapse. This results in decreased breath sounds and a dull percussion note on physical examination.\r\n\r\nThe absence of specific signs of infection, such as an altered sputum with bacteria or inflammatory cells, suggests that the atelectasis is not due to infection, such as bronchiopneumonia or lung abscess. Instead, it is a mechanical obstruction resulting in the collapse of the lung tissue.","reference":"Grott K, Chauhan S, Dunlap JD. Atelectasis. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 20, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545316/","responses":[{"text":"Lung abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumothorax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Resorptive atelectasis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchietelectasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiopneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11776,"text":"Which of the following is an example of a secondary pollutant?","explanation":"An example of a secondary pollutant is **ozone at ground level**. Unlike primary pollutants, which are directly emitted into the atmosphere, secondary pollutants are formed through chemical reactions involving primary pollutants and other substances present in the atmosphere.\r\n\r\nIn the case of ozone, it is not directly emitted into the air but is formed as a result of chemical reactions between nitrogen oxides (NOx) and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) in the presence of sunlight. These precursor pollutants, primarily emitted from human activities such as industrial processes and vehicular emissions, undergo photochemical reactions to produce ozone.","reference":"Franklin M, Schwartz J. The impact of secondary particles on the association between ambient ozone and mortality. Environmental Health Perspectives. Published April 2008. Accessed May 20, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2290974/","responses":[{"text":"CO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ozone at ground level","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ozone in higher atmosphere","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SO2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"NO2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11777,"text":"Which of following will confirm that a parapneumonic effusion has changed into empyema?","explanation":"A **pH value less than 7** is an indicator that a parapneumonic effusion has changed into empyema. Parapneumonic effusion refers to the accumulation of fluid in the pleural space as a result of an underlying pneumonia. In some cases, the effusion may progress to empyema, which is characterized by the presence of purulent material (pus) in the pleural space.\r\n\r\nThe pH of the fluid can help differentiate between a parapneumonic effusion and empyema. A pH below 7 indicates the presence of an acidic environment, which is commonly seen in empyema due to the accumulation of bacteria and the release of inflammatory mediators. A pH value above 7 suggests a more sterile or non-infected fluid, which is typically observed in uncomplicated parapneumonic effusions.\r\n\r\nOther laboratory parameters such as the pleural LDH to serum LDH ratio, pleural glucose to serum glucose ratio, and the presence of a high number of red blood cells (RBCs) can also provide additional diagnostic information. However, the pH value is a reliable indicator for confirming the transformation of a parapneumonic effusion into empyema.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 564.","responses":[{"text":"Pleural LDH to serum LDH ratio \u003c 0.6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH \u003c 7","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"pH \u003e 7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"RBC \u003e1000","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural glucose to serum glucose ratio \u003e 1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11778,"text":"Which of the following defines granulomas?","explanation":"Granulomas are defined as **chronic inflammatory responses characterized by the accumulation of macrophages**. These macrophages are transformed into epithelioid cells, which have a distinct appearance with abundant cytoplasm and indistinct cell boundaries. Granulomas also typically contain multinucleated giant cells, which are formed by the fusion of macrophages.\r\n\r\nThe formation of granulomas is usually triggered by persistent infections or the presence of foreign materials that the immune system is unable to eliminate. The macrophages within the granuloma attempt to contain the offending agent by surrounding it and forming a barrier. In addition to macrophages and giant cells, granulomas may also contain lymphocytes and fibroblasts.\r\n\r\nGranulomas are a hallmark feature of certain infectious diseases, such as tuberculosis and leprosy, as well as autoimmune conditions like sarcoidosis. They play a role in walling off the offending agent and limiting its spread within the body.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 97.","responses":[{"text":"Active inflammation composed of basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute on chronic inflammation composed of macrophages and neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic inflammation composed of macrophages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Active inflammation composed of macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Active inflammation composed of eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11779,"text":"According to pathogenesis, how many types of granulomas are present?","explanation":"According to pathogenesis, there are **two** types of granulomas: **foreign-body granulomas** and **immune granulomas**.\r\n\r\nForeign body granulomas occur in response to the presence of non-biological foreign materials within the tissues. These granulomas are formed by macrophages surrounding and engulfing the foreign material, resulting in the formation of multinucleated giant cells. The foreign body granulomas typically lack lymphocytes and are characterized by the absence of an immune response.\r\n\r\nImmune granulomas, on the other hand, are formed in response to persistent infections or immune-mediated diseases. They are characterized by the presence of lymphocytes, activated macrophages, and epithelioid cells. In immune granulomas, the antigenic stimulus triggers the activation of T-helper lymphocytes, leading to the production of cytokines that recruit and activate macrophages. The activated macrophages, along with other immune cells, form the granulomatous structure.\r\n\r\nThese two types of granulomas represent distinct pathways of the body's response to different stimuli, with foreign body granulomas primarily driven by physical factors and immune granulomas associated with immune responses.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 97.","responses":[{"text":"6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11780,"text":"Which is the most important side effect of salbutamol that is dose-dependent?","explanation":"**Muscle tremors** are the most important dose-dependent side effect of salbutamol. Salbutamol is a selective beta-2 adrenergic receptor agonist commonly used as a bronchodilator in the treatment of asthma and other respiratory conditions. Activation of beta-2 receptors leads to relaxation of bronchial smooth muscles, resulting in bronchodilation and relief of symptoms.\r\n\r\nHowever, salbutamol can also bind to beta-2 receptors in skeletal muscles, particularly at higher doses. This can lead to the stimulation of skeletal muscle cells and subsequent tremors. Muscle tremors are the most common side effect observed with salbutamol use, especially when administered via inhalation.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that these tremors are generally transient and dose-dependent. They tend to subside as the body adjusts to the medication or when the dosage is reduced. Patients should be educated about this potential side effect to alleviate any concerns and ensure proper adherence to their treatment regimen.","reference":"(1) Nizet TAC. Tremor side effects of salbutamol, quantified by a laser pointer technique. Respiratory Medicine. Published September 1, 2004. Accessed May 10, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0954611104000964 (2) Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 708.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscle tremors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depression","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11781,"text":"What are the changes observed in pulmonary hypertension?","explanation":"In pulmonary hypertension, the characteristic changes observed in the pulmonary arteries include **medial hypertrophy**. Pulmonary hypertension refers to the elevation of blood pressure in the pulmonary circulation, which can lead to various structural and functional changes in the pulmonary vessels.\r\n\r\nMedial hypertrophy refers to the thickening of the muscular layer (media) of the pulmonary artery walls. This thickening occurs as a result of smooth muscle cell proliferation and hypertrophy. The increased muscularity of the vessel wall contributes to the elevated resistance to blood flow in the pulmonary circulation.\r\n\r\nOther changes observed in pulmonary hypertension may include intimal hyperplasia, which refers to the thickening of the innermost layer (intima) of the vessel wall, and vascular remodeling, which involves changes in the composition and arrangement of the extracellular matrix.\r\n\r\nThese structural changes in the pulmonary vessels contribute to the increased resistance to blood flow and can eventually lead to right ventricular hypertrophy and heart failure.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 700.","responses":[{"text":"Intimal hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial atrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial hypertrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intimal thickening","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11782,"text":"Which of the following best describes the pathogenesis of tuberculosis?","explanation":"The pathogenesis of tuberculosis involves the **activation of Th1 immune response by the production of interferon-gamma (IFN-γ) by macrophages**. Tuberculosis is caused by the bacterium Mycobacterium tuberculosis, which primarily infects macrophages in the lungs.\r\n\r\nUpon infection, M. tuberculosis is phagocytosed by macrophages and survives within the phagosomes. Infected macrophages release various cytokines, including interleukin-12 (IL-12), which stimulates the differentiation of naïve T cells into Th1 cells.\r\n\r\nTh1 cells produce IFN-γ, which plays a crucial role in the immune response against M. tuberculosis. IFN-γ activates macrophages, enhancing their antimicrobial activity and promoting the formation of granulomas, which are characteristic of tuberculosis.\r\n\r\nGranulomas are organized structures composed of infected macrophages, activated T cells, and other immune cells. They serve as a site of containment for the infection, preventing the spread of M. tuberculosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 372.","responses":[{"text":"Activation of th1 by production of interferon-gamma by macrophages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of th2 by production of interferon-gamma by macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of th2 by production of interferon-gamma by neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of th1 by production of interferon-gamma by basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of th1 by production of interferon-gamma by neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11783,"text":"Petechiae are absent in which kind of death?","explanation":"Petechiae, which are pinpoint-sized red or purple spots on the skin caused by bleeding into the small blood vessels, are typically absent in cases of **drowning**. \r\n\r\nPetechiae occur due to increased pressure within the blood vessels, causing them to rupture and leak blood into the surrounding tissues. In cases of strangulation, lynching, traumatic asphyxia, and garroting, there is compression or constriction of the neck, leading to increased pressure in the blood vessels. This increased pressure can cause petechiae to develop in the face, eyes, and other areas of the body.\r\n\r\nHowever, in drowning, there is no external pressure applied to the neck. Instead, drowning occurs due to the inhalation of water or other fluids, leading to asphyxia. The absence of external pressure on the neck means there is no significant increase in blood vessel pressure, and therefore petechiae are typically not present in cases of drowning.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that the absence of petechiae does not definitively rule out drowning as a cause of death, as other findings and circumstances must be considered in conjunction with the absence of petechiae to make a proper determination.","reference":"Vij K. Textbook of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology Principles and Practice. 5th ed. Elsevier; 2011: 23.","responses":[{"text":"Strangulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lynching","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Garroting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drowning","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Traumatic asphyxia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11785,"text":"A collective dose of radiation to a population can be expressed in which unit?","explanation":"A collective dose of radiation to a population is expressed in the unit called **person-Sievert (person-Sv)**. The person-Sievert is a measure that combines both the quantity and the biological effect of radiation exposure. It takes into account the number of individuals exposed and the average radiation dose received by each individual.\r\n\r\nThe Sievert (Sv) is a unit of equivalent dose that quantifies the biological effect of radiation on human tissues. It takes into consideration the type of radiation and its potential for causing harm. By multiplying the average dose received by each individual in a population by the number of individuals exposed, we obtain the collective dose in person-Sievert.\r\n\r\nThis unit is commonly used in epidemiological studies and risk assessments to evaluate the health effects of radiation exposure on a population. It helps in understanding the overall impact of radiation on a larger scale and aids in making informed decisions regarding radiation safety and protection measures.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Respiratory module, Forensic slides, Topic: Nuclear medicine.","responses":[{"text":"Rad","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Person-Sievert","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sievert","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Becquerel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Curie","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11786,"text":"Which of the following is least likely to cause a radiation hazard?","explanation":"Among the options listed, **MRI (magnetic resonance imaging) of the abdomen** is least likely to cause a radiation hazard compared to the other imaging modalities. \r\n\r\nMRI uses a strong magnetic field and radio waves to generate detailed images of the body. Unlike CT scans and X-rays, MRI does not involve the use of ionizing radiation. Instead, it relies on the interaction of magnetic fields with the body's natural alignment of hydrogen atoms. As a result, MRI does not pose a radiation hazard to patients.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, CT scans, X-rays, and fluoroscopic imaging (such as upper GI series and lower GI series) all use ionizing radiation, which carries potential risks related to radiation exposure. The radiation dose and associated hazards vary depending on factors such as the type of examination, the body area being imaged, and the number of exposures.","reference":"Ghadimi M, Sapra A. Magnetic resonance imaging contraindications. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 20, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551669/","responses":[{"text":"CT head","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower GI series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI abdomen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper GI series","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11788,"text":"A patient had lung cancer and doctors commented that it can not be removed surgically. Which of the following is it most likely to be?","explanation":"**Small cell carcinoma of the lung** is an aggressive type of lung cancer that tends to grow and spread rapidly. It is typically associated with a poor prognosis and is often diagnosed at an advanced stage when surgical removal is no longer feasible.\r\n\r\nSmall cell carcinoma accounts for approximately 10-15% of all lung cancers and is strongly associated with smoking. It is characterized by small, tightly packed cells with scant cytoplasm and high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio. Microscopically, it exhibits a characteristic appearance with extensive necrosis and a high mitotic rate.\r\n\r\nDue to its aggressive nature and propensity for early metastasis, small cell carcinoma of the lung is typically managed with chemotherapy and radiation therapy rather than surgery. This multimodal treatment approach aims to target both the primary tumor and any potential metastatic spread.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 96.","responses":[{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoid tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small cell carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Large cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11789,"text":"A person commits suicide by slitting his throat, and dies of an air embolism. How did air enter his circulation?","explanation":"The **jugular veins** are major veins that drain deoxygenated blood from the head and neck and return it to the heart. When the throat is slit, the integrity of the neck structures, including the veins, is compromised, allowing air to enter the vasculature.\r\n\r\nThe entry of air into the jugular vein can occur due to the negative pressure created during inspiration. If the person takes a breath after slitting their throat, air can be drawn into the veins through the open wound. This air can then travel through the venous system and potentially reach the heart and other organs, causing an air embolism.\r\n\r\nAn air embolism occurs when air bubbles obstruct blood flow, leading to impaired circulation and tissue damage. In the case of a jugular vein air embolism, the air bubbles can be carried to the heart and then dispersed throughout the body, affecting various organs and tissues.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 301.","responses":[{"text":"Jugular vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vertrebral artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11790,"text":"Which of the following is released by macrophages to activate Th1?","explanation":"Macrophages play a crucial role in activating the Th1 immune response by releasing specific cytokines. One of the key cytokines released by macrophages to activate Th1 cells is **interleukin-12 (IL-12)**. IL-12 acts as a bridge between the innate and adaptive immune responses by promoting the differentiation of naive T cells into Th1 cells.\r\n\r\nUpon encountering antigens, macrophages phagocytose and process them, leading to the presentation of antigenic peptides on their cell surface. This activates the macrophages to secrete IL-12. IL-12, in turn, binds to its receptor on naive T cells, promoting their differentiation into Th1 cells. Th1 cells are responsible for initiating cell-mediated immune responses and activating cytotoxic T cells, which are important in clearing intracellular pathogens.\r\n\r\nIL-12 also enhances the production of interferon-gamma (IFN-gamma) by Th1 cells, further amplifying the Th1 response. IFN-gamma plays a critical role in activating macrophages to enhance their phagocytic and bactericidal functions.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 372.","responses":[{"text":"IL-6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IL-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IL-12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IL-8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"TNF-gamma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11791,"text":"A professor is teaching his students about research. He tells them that the problem statement should be clear and measurable. Which part of the project should be error-free to achieve this?","explanation":"In a research project, the **objective** is a crucial component that should be clear and measurable. The objective defines the specific goal or purpose of the study, and it provides direction and focus to the research process. It states what the researcher aims to achieve and the outcomes they intend to measure.\r\n\r\nAn error-free objective is essential for several reasons. First, a clear objective helps to ensure that the research question is well-defined and unambiguous. It provides a framework for designing the study and selecting appropriate methods and measurements. Second, a measurable objective allows for the evaluation of research outcomes and the determination of whether the study has achieved its intended goals. It enables researchers to assess the effectiveness of interventions, compare results to established benchmarks, and make meaningful conclusions.\r\n\r\nAn objective should be specific, concise, and achievable. It should clearly state the population or sample under study, the variables of interest, and the desired outcome or impact. By formulating an error-free objective, researchers can ensure that their study is focused, rigorous, and capable of generating meaningful findings.","reference":"Farrugia P, Petrisor BA, Farrokhyar F, Bhandari M. Research questions, hypotheses and objectives. Canadian Journal of Surgery. Published August 2010. Accessed May 20, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2912019/","responses":[{"text":"Results","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Introduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Discussion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methodology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Objective","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11792,"text":"What part of visible spectrum of light does most damage to the eyes?","explanation":"**Blue light** is the part of the visible spectrum that is most damaging to the eyes. It has a shorter wavelength and higher energy compared to other colors of light. When our eyes are exposed to blue light for extended periods, it can lead to various ocular problems and potential damage.\r\n\r\nThe primary concern with blue light is its ability to penetrate the structures of the eye, including the cornea and lens, and reach the retina. Prolonged exposure to blue light has been linked to retinal damage and an increased risk of developing age-related macular degeneration (AMD). AMD is a progressive eye condition that can result in vision loss and impairment.\r\n\r\nIn today's digital world, we are exposed to significant amounts of blue light from electronic devices such as smartphones, tablets, and computers. It is essential to take measures to protect our eyes, such as using blue light filters on screens, wearing blue light-blocking glasses, and taking regular breaks from screen time.","reference":"Mechanisms of blue light-induced eye hazard and protective measures: a review. Biomedicine \u0026 Pharmacotherapy. Published October 1, 2020. Accessed May 11, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753332220307708","responses":[{"text":"Red","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Yellow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orange","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Green","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11793,"text":"Which vertebral fracture occurs in judicial hanging?","explanation":"In judicial hanging, the most common vertebral fracture occurs at the level of **C2-C3**. This is known as the hangman's fracture or traumatic spondylolisthesis of C2. It is caused by the sudden and extreme force applied to the neck during hanging.\r\n\r\nThe hangman's fracture typically results from hyperextension and distraction forces on the cervical spine. It involves a fracture through the pedicles or pars interarticularis of C2 (axis), along with anterior displacement of C2 relative to C3. This fracture disrupts the ligaments and bony structures that stabilize the cervical spine.\r\n\r\nThe C2-C3 level is vulnerable to injury during hanging because it is the weakest part of the cervical spine, with a relatively mobile articulation. The fracture can be associated with spinal cord injury and is considered a severe and potentially life-threatening injury.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 167.","responses":[{"text":"C8-T1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C2-C3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C3-C4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C1-C2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T1-T2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11794,"text":"Which incision is made for the dissection of skullcap?","explanation":"The correct incision for the dissection of the skullcap is from the **right mastoid to the left mastoid over the occipital region**. This incision is known as a **\"Y-shaped\"** incision.\r\n\r\nThe Y-shaped incision is commonly used in forensic autopsies to access and examine the brain. It involves making an incision from the right mastoid process to the left mastoid process, passing over the occipital region of the skull. This incision allows for easy reflection of the scalp and access to the calvarium (skullcap).\r\n\r\nBy using this incision, the forensic pathologist can carefully remove the calvarium, providing a clear view of the brain for examination. It allows for the examination of the intracranial structures, including the brain, meninges, and blood vessels.","reference":"1) Bakkannavar SM. Forensic Medicine and Toxicology Practical Manual, 1st Edition - e-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017: 124. \r\n\r\n2) Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015.","responses":[{"text":"Frontal to foreman magnum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right mastoid to left mastoid through falx cerebri","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left mastoid to right parietal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left parietal to right parietal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right mastoid to left mastoid over the occipital region","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16127,"text":"Which of the following conditions is characterized by rounded or stellate granulomas containing central granular debris and neutrophils?","explanation":"**Cat-scratch disease**, caused by the bacterium ***Bartonella henselae***, is typically associated with a history of a scratch or bite from a cat. The hallmark histopathological feature of cat-scratch disease is the **presence of granulomas with a distinctive stellate or star-shaped structure**, often containing central necrosis with granular debris and neutrophils.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nTuberculosis is caused by *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, typically presents with caseating granulomas, characterized by a necrotic center with a granular appearance.\r\n\r\nSarcoidosis is characterized by non-caseating granulomas, which are compact and well-formed, lacking central necrosis.\r\n\r\nBrucellosis is caused by *Brucella* species, does not typically form granulomas. When it does, they are not of the stellate type seen in cat-scratch disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 101.","responses":[{"text":"Cat-scratch disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brucellosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

